data.content:
Here's what breaks in each case and the fixes:

## 1. Buffer.cs — `[InlineArray]` on record struct banned

C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` types (the synthesized `Equals`/`GetHashCode` would only compare the first element).

**Fix:** Use a plain `struct`:

```csharp
[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]
struct Buffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

## 2. Generator.cs — `stackalloc` in iterator local function

C# 13 lifted the blanket ban on `unsafe` in iterators. A side-effect is the compiler now processes `unsafe` local functions as part of the iterator state machine, where `stackalloc` is still illegal (the stack frame is suspended across yields).

**Fix:** Extract the unsafe work to a separate `static` method outside the iterator:

```csharp
unsafe class DataGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<int> Generate()
    {
        yield return 1;
        Process();
    }

    static unsafe void Process()
    {
        int* p = stackalloc int[10];
        // ... work with pointer
    }
}
```

## 3. Resolver.cs — Collection expression overload ambiguity

C# 13 improved collection-expression conversions so `[]` is now equally convertible to both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`, making the call ambiguous.

**Fix:** Disambiguate with an explicit cast:

```csharp
static void Main()
{
    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);
}
```
